24 in 2024

I have 2 very full shelves of unread books, many of which have been sitting there unread for well over a year. To help me reduce this list slightly, I am participating in the 24 in 24 challenge. It was hard choosing only 24 backlist books that I wanted to commit to reading this year, and tbh this is about my 5th stack that I took pics of. But I think this is a list worth sticking to. I decided for this challenge to prioritize diversifying my reading and I chose books from authors that represent different perspectives - Iâ€™m hoping in 2024 to continue to be intentional about reading books from LGBTQIA+ and BIPOC authors but also books that share other perspectives such as disabilities, religions, etc. and I thought this list was a great place to start. Iâ€™m excited to dive into these books this year. Let me know if you see any favorites in this stack.

Huge thanks to @bookswithnopictures and @lemonyreads for hosting this #backlistbooks24 challenge!

This painting tells the story of the transgression of Xochiquetzal, Our Lady the Plumed Flower, She Who is Love. Before the birth of existence, the Teteo lived in Tamoanchan, the Twelfth Heaven, the celestial palace of beauty and abundance. Xochiquetzal fell in love with the Sacred Tree, the column which communicates the levels of the cosmos: the Underworld, the Earth and the Heavens. She was convinced by Huehuecoyotl, Lord of Deceit, to cut one of its flowers. She severed a branch of the Sacred Tree, and it immediately started to bleed. The Teteo were sucked in by the Tree. They traveled through its trunk and were expelled at the Earth, where They became all things material and mortal. To be alive, thus, is to participate in the death of the Teteo, who are living in our food, our clothes, our tools and our weapons.

Gonzalez traces the issue to her time in college, when she read third-wave feminist texts by day and danced with her schoolâ€™s small coterie of Latino students by night: â€œThe chasm between the bodily autonomy I was being empowered to have intellectually and the physical pliability to a partnerâ€™s will that salsa required was simply too wide for my teenage brain to bridge.â€ â 
â 
Years later, Gonzalez realized she was missing out on the fun of the dance. She enrolled in a salsa class in Brooklyn, where â€œit became clear that what was keeping me from being a better dance partner was not really about dancing at all â€¦ I realized in that salsa studio that even when someone had been dancing next to me, I had been dancing alone.â€ Gonzalez considers herself a happy and successful independent woman, but learning to be a good salsa dancer, which required making space for her dance partner, caused her to question whether she could make space for someone else in her life: â€œI donâ€™t mean â€˜Could I meet someone?â€™ I mean â€˜Could I coexist in an intimate partnership the way that I am currently programmed?â€™ And Iâ€™m not so certain what the answer is.â€â

Le tenemos miedo a la muerte, sin darnos cuenta que morimos en vida una y mil veces..

En cada proceso, cada cambio, cada movimiento..

El movimiento real de la vida es en cÃ­rculos, espiralado. Una espiral que produce la sensaciÃ³n de ir hacia delante y hacia lo desconocido permanentemente, nunca se vuelve al mismo lugar. 

Nuevas estrellas nacen mientras otras mueren.

Muere el presente en cada instante, 
para convertirse en pasado.

Estamos destinados al final de todo comienzo.. pero porque eso tiene que ser malo? 

Si en cada duelo, crece una nueva semilla, 
se expresa la creatividad del universo, 
en una nueva flor.

Es momento de aprender a vivir y funcionar en circulo, en repeticiÃ³n y en novedad simultÃ¡neamente. 

De convivir sanamente con el eterno miedo 
a la incertidumbre.

La vida no es llegar a una meta, ni es inmortalizarnos o evitar el final..

La vida es hacia adelante y sin destino.
Un constante florecer.

THANK YOU for this amazing book mail, Flatiron Books! I may or may not have paraded around my living room holding it up like it was baby Simba at the beginning of The Lion Kingâ€¦ for longer than I should admit. The watercolor was also a clever tie in, thank you for that too.

Yâ€™all, Anita de Monte Laughs Last has been at the top of my must read list since I found out about it last year. Xochitl Gonzalez also wrote Olga Dies Dreaming which was one of my top ten reads of 2022 so I truly canâ€™t tell you how excited I am to jump in. Here is the publisherâ€™s summary, let me know if youâ€™ll be picking it up too. (Arrives March 5, 2024.)

Publisherâ€™s Summary:
1985. Anita de Monte, a rising star in the art world, is found dead in New York City; her tragic death is the talk of the town. Until it isnâ€™t. By 1998 Anitaâ€™s name has been all but forgottenâ€”certainly by the time Raquel, a third-year art history student is preparing her final thesis. On College Hill, surrounded by privileged students whose futures are already paved out for them, Raquel feels like an outsider. Students of color, like her, are the minority there, and the pressure to work twice as hard for the same opportunities is no secret.

But when Raquel becomes romantically involved with a well-connected older art student, she finds herself unexpectedly rising up the social ranks. As she attempts to straddle both worlds, she stumbles upon Anitaâ€™s story, raising questions about the dynamics of her own relationship, which eerily mirrors that of the forgotten artist.

Moving back and forth through time and told from the perspectives of both women, Anita de Monte Laughs Last is a propulsive, witty examination of power, love, and art, daring to ask who gets to be remembered and who is left behind in the rarefied world of the elite.
